Creating Shot Charts

Todays main focus is going to be on creating cool visualizations, both because its fun and because it can teach us a lot about basketball. Specifically were going to focus on shot charts.

The first thing we need is shot data, including information on the location of each shot.

Lab Activity 1: First lets take a moment to talk about how might we encode the location of a shot on a basketball court in a way that a computer could understand and that could be entered into a database?







Getting Shot Data

OK, now we need to get this data - lets say for all shots from the 2018-19 season. Luckily the NBA actually has this data publicly accessible through an Application Programming Interface (API).

What the hell is an API? Its a way for computers to talk to each other, basically. The most common use youll have for it as a sports analyst is to use your computer to request data from another computer - in this specific case, from the NBAs database servers.

Working directly with the NBAs API can be quite difficult. Fortunately, Saiem Gilani has written the hoopR (get it???) package with a bunch of useful functions to help us out. (The hoopR package also works with mens college basketball data. The package ncaahoopR also works for mens college basketball data. The package wncaahoopR accesses data for the womens college game. Im uncertain of a package for the WNBA but it may exist - if you find one let me know!)

OK, heres the code wed use to get this data for the 2018-19 season. DONT USE IT. We dont want to flood the NBA Stats API with a bunch of requests for 220,000 shots. Im just including it so you know what it looks like.

shots18 <- nba_shotchartdetail(
  context_measure = "FGA",
  date_from = "",
  date_to = "",
  game_id = "",
  game_segment = "",
  last_n_games = 0,
  league_id = "00",
  location = "",
  month = 0,
  opponent_team_id = 0,
  outcome = "",
  period = 0,
  player_id = "0", # This is "0" to indicate we want all players. You'd use a specific player's ID (more in a moment) here to get the data just for them
  player_position = "",
  rookie_year = "",
  season = "2018-19", # We want the 2018-19 season
  season_segment = "",
  season_type = "Regular Season", # Want regular season, not playoffs
  team_id = 0,
  vs_conference = "",
  vs_division = ""
)[[1]]

Lab Activity 2: Can you intuit how you might change the code above to get, say, shot data for all players for just the last 30 days (if you were doing this mid-season)?

Note the [[1]] on the last line. This probably looks impenetrable to you. I dont want to get into what it means right now except to say it changes the data from a list (a flexible type of data structure in R) to the more familiar rectangular data frame.

Do You Have a Moment to Talk About Working Directories?

To import data from a file, we first need to know how R looks for files.

Whenever you open RStudio it sets a working directory, which is the place where its going to look for (or in the case of exporting, try to write) any files by default, unless you specify otherwise. You can see where it is using the getwd() command. Try it in your own script.

#Find out what your working directory is
getwd()

I typically want my working directory to be either:

  1. The folder where the script Im working in is located, OR

  2. If its part of an R Project the parent directory for the project itself (we havent learned about these yet, please dont worry about them).

But what if you use getwd() and notice R/RStudio has chosen a different working directory for some reason?

There are two ways to set the working directory to be the location of the file youre working in. I usually like to include this code in the top of my files:

#Set the working directory to be the location of the script 
#or R Markdown document you're working in
setwd(dirname(rstudioapi::getActiveDocumentContext()$path))

Alternatively, more recent versions of RStudio allow you to do this manually by going to the top menu and clicking Session > Set Working Directory... > To Source File Location.

Lab Activity 4: Set your working directory to be the location of this script.

Once we set a working directory we can tell R to search for a file in that directory very easily with the code below.

shots18 <- read.csv("./shots_1819.csv")

The . means look in the working directory. I couldve also fed a full file path (for example, "C:/Users/zbinney/OneDrive - Emory University/Statistics in Sports/R_Labs_and_Homeworks/shots_1819.csv"), but isnt our code much cleaner? It will also work more easily on multiple machines, whereas the full file path will only work on my laptop.

shots18 <- shots18 %>% 
  
  #Change shot units to feet
  mutate(LOC_X = LOC_X/10,
         LOC_Y = LOC_Y/10) %>%
  
  # Calculate more precise shot distance
  mutate(SHOT_DISTANCE = sqrt(LOC_X^2 + LOC_Y^2))

Interlude: Data Cleaning

An unsexy but very necessary part of sports analytis is data cleaning. A lot of data, when you get it, is full of errors and other weird issues - mis-formatted variables, typos, implausible data values, and other incorrect or otherwise un-analyzable data.

Many data analysts report spending 60-80% of their time just prepping data for analysis, not doing actual analyses. This is consistent with my experience. But, to try and just get you interested in the field were skipping over a lot of this stuff and working with pre-cleaned because people find cleaning boring.

Still, I want to give you at least a little experience with the type of cleaning youll have to do in the real world. The NBA API involves a lot of data quality checks and processes to clean the data before sending it out, so this is one of the better datasets youll ever get. But even then you always want to check for issues.

A good place to start is by running a simple summary() on the data frame and looking for anything implausible or downright impossible:

Lets now check for implausible records of shots. In the NBA, the distance the 3-pt line is from the hoops ranges from 22 feet in the corners to 23.75 feet at the top of the arc. Armed with this knowledge, are there any implausible shots in our data?

First lets check the top and bottom few shot distances for 2-pt shots:

Lab Activity 7: Do you see any shots that worry you? Or any data that needs to be cleaned?

If we identified something that needed to be addressed, wed have two basic options:

  1. Delete the offending observations entirely using filter(). This is probably fine if its a small number of shots, but you never want to throw out data - and especially a meaningfully large proportion of your data - if you can avoid it. Heres some example code, though:
shots18_clean <- shots18 %>% 
  filter(SHOT_DIST>=21 | SHOT_TYPE == "2PT Field Goal") # Filter OUT shots that don't meet EITHER criterion (21 feet or longer OR 2 pts)
  1. Correct the data. This is tricky though because it requires finding - or assuming - some truth. For example, when whether the shot is a 2- or 3-pointer conflicts with the shot distance, which is correct? You could go back and look at game film for every borderline shot, but that would take days. Its always a balancing act, and looking up case-by-case truths becomes less possible the larger the data youre working with is.

Hopefully this looks kind of familiar already. But it would probably be nicer to have a court overlaid as the background, right? To do this were going to use the plot_court() function from Todd Schneiders ballr (get it? get it???) package. (ballr actually allows you to create interactive shot charts very easily, but I wanted to peel back the layers of the onion a little and show you how to do it yourself.)

Unfortuantely R doesnt know plot_court() - we have to teach it to R. Thats what the code below is doing. Its going to look very scary - dont worry about interpreting it. Just know its basically teaching R how to draw a basketball court. Thats it.

court_themes = list(
  light = list(
    court = '#fffcf2',
    lines = '#999999',
    text = '#222222',
    made = '#00bfc4',
    missed = '#f8766d',
    hex_border_size = 0.3,
    hex_border_color = "#cccccc"
  ),
  dark = list(
    court = '#000004',
    lines = '#999999',
    text = '#f0f0f0',
    made = '#00bfc4',
    missed = '#f8766d',
    hex_border_size = 0,
    hex_border_color = "#000000"
  )
)

circle_points = function(center = c(0, 0), radius = 1, npoints = 360) {
  angles = seq(0, 2 * pi, length.out = npoints)
  return(tibble(x = center[1] + radius * cos(angles),
                    y = center[2] + radius * sin(angles)))
}

width = 50
height = 94 / 2
key_height = 19
inner_key_width = 12
outer_key_width = 16
backboard_width = 6
backboard_offset = 4
neck_length = 0.5
hoop_radius = 0.75
hoop_center_y = backboard_offset + neck_length + hoop_radius
three_point_radius = 23.75
three_point_side_radius = 22
three_point_side_height = 14

plot_court = function(court_theme = court_themes$dark, use_short_three = FALSE) {
  if (use_short_three) {
    three_point_radius = 22
    three_point_side_height = 0
  }

  court_points = tibble(
    x = c(width / 2, width / 2, -width / 2, -width / 2, width / 2),
    y = c(height, 0, 0, height, height),
    desc = "perimeter"
  )

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(outer_key_width / 2, outer_key_width / 2, -outer_key_width / 2, -outer_key_width / 2),
    y = c(0, key_height, key_height, 0),
    desc = "outer_key"
  ))

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(-backboard_width / 2, backboard_width / 2),
    y = c(backboard_offset, backboard_offset),
    desc = "backboard"
  ))

  court_points = bind_rows(court_points , tibble(
    x = c(0, 0), y = c(backboard_offset, backboard_offset + neck_length), desc = "neck"
  ))

  foul_circle = circle_points(center = c(0, key_height), radius = inner_key_width / 2)

  foul_circle_top = filter(foul_circle, y > key_height) %>%
    mutate(desc = "foul_circle_top")

  foul_circle_bottom = filter(foul_circle, y < key_height) %>%
    mutate(
      angle = atan((y - key_height) / x) * 180 / pi,
      angle_group = floor((angle - 5.625) / 11.25),
      desc = paste0("foul_circle_bottom_", angle_group)
    ) %>%
    filter(angle_group %% 2 == 0) %>%
    select(x, y, desc)

  hoop = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = hoop_radius) %>%
    mutate(desc = "hoop")

  restricted = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = 4) %>%
    filter(y >= hoop_center_y) %>%
    mutate(desc = "restricted")

  three_point_circle = circle_points(center = c(0, hoop_center_y), radius = three_point_radius) %>%
    filter(y >= three_point_side_height, y >= hoop_center_y)

  three_point_line = tibble(
    x = c(three_point_side_radius, three_point_side_radius, three_point_circle$x, -three_point_side_radius, -three_point_side_radius),
    y = c(0, three_point_side_height, three_point_circle$y, three_point_side_height, 0),
    desc = "three_point_line"
  )

  court_points = bind_rows(
    court_points,
    foul_circle_top,
    foul_circle_bottom,
    hoop,
    restricted,
    three_point_line
  )

  court_points <<- court_points

  ggplot() +
    geom_path(
      data = court_points,
      aes(x = x, y = y, group = desc),
      color = court_theme$lines
    ) +
    coord_fixed(ylim = c(0, 35), xlim = c(-25, 25)) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 16) +
    theme(
      text = element_text(color = court_theme$text),
      plot.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      panel.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      panel.grid = element_blank(),
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.text = element_blank(),
      axis.title = element_blank(),
      axis.ticks = element_blank(),
      legend.background = element_rect(fill = court_theme$court, color = court_theme$court),
      legend.margin = margin(-1, 0, 0, 0, unit = "lines"),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      legend.key = element_blank(),
      legend.text = element_text(size = rel(0.7))
    )
}

Now that weve taught R how to plot a court, we can add it to our plot above for Jaylen Brown!

Plotting Expected Value of Shots

In the lecture we talked about the expected values of various shots. Lets investigate that further now.

The coordinates we have are so specific theyll result in very small sample sizes if we dont bin them. Specifically, well bin them into areas that are 1 foot in width and height.

# Bin our data before plotting
shots18_bin <- shots18 %>% 
  mutate(LOC_X_feet = round(LOC_X, 0), # Round X and Y locations to the nearest foot to create bins
         LOC_Y_feet = round(LOC_Y + hoop_center_y, 0),
         
         pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot to allow for expected value calculations
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>%
  
  # Create new variables for number of shots and percentage of shots made in each bin
  # as well as whether a bin had >550 shot attempts in a year (roughly, a top-50 location)
  group_by(LOC_X_feet, LOC_Y_feet) %>% 
  summarize(FGA = n(),
            FGpct = mean(SHOT_MADE_FLAG),
            exp_pts = round(mean(SHOT_MADE_FLAG*pts),1),
            FGA_top50 = case_when(FGA >= 550 ~ 1,
                                  TRUE ~ 0)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'LOC_X_feet'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
# Create base court plot
base_court <- plot_court(court_themes$light)

#Plot expected value and number of shots by bin

base_court + 
  
  geom_point(data = shots18_bin %>% filter(FGA >= 50), # Exclude points with <50 FGA
             aes(x = LOC_X_feet, y = LOC_Y_feet, 
                 color = exp_pts, size = FGA)) + # Color points by expected value, size by FGA
  
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(0.5,4), # Manually set min and max point size 
                        guide = "none") + # Remove size legend
  
  scale_color_viridis_c(option = "D", # Use pretty viridis color scheme rather than default
                        breaks = c(0.4, 0.8, 1.2, 1.6), labels = c(0.4, 0.8, 1.2, 1.6)) + # Manually set color legend labels

  # Specify axis labels, title, subtitle, caption, and color legend label
  labs(X = "", y = "", title = "Expected Shot Value by Location",
  subtitle = "2018-19 Regular Season\n Locations with >= 50 Shots",
  caption = "Size proportional to number of attempts. \n Darker spots are top 50 shot locations.",
  color = "Expected Points") +
  
  theme(legend.title = element_text(size = 10), # Change legend title and text font size
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10), 
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14), # Change title size and center align
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12), # Change subtitle size and center align
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 8)) + # Change caption size
  
  guides(color = guide_colourbar(title.position="top", hjust = 0.5)) # Place color legend label on top of scale and center align

Assessing Player Types

Lets continue working with our shot data. Lets begin by summarizing each players performance over the course of the season. If a player played on multiple teams well give him a different line for each team since his usage and performance could have changed from team to team:

players18 <- shots18 %>% 
  mutate(pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  group_by(PLAYER_NAME, TEAM_NAME) %>% 
  summarize(FGA = n(), # Count rows to get FGA
            FGM = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG), # Sum um 0/1 SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get FGM
            
            # Do a "Count If" equivalent to get number of 2 pt and 3pt FGA
            FGA_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2])/2,
            FGA_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3])/3,
            
            # Multiply those "count ifs" by SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get number of each type of FGM
            FGM_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==2])/2,
            FGM_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==3])/3) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'PLAYER_NAME'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Mr.Heroball

Well define Heroball as taking the highest percentage of your teams shots.

First we need the number of shots each team took. We can get this from another dataset of team box scores available in hoopR:

# Load 2018 team box score data
team_box18 <- load_nba_team_box(2018)


# Calculate shots per team
team_data18 <- team_box18 %>% 
  
  # Extract FGA as the 4th character through the end from the character variable `field_goals_made...`
  mutate(FGA = as.numeric(str_sub(field_goals_made_field_goals_attempted, start = 4))) %>% 

  group_by(team_display_name, team_abbreviation) %>% 
  summarize(FGA_team = sum(FGA)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'team_display_name'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Lab Activity 13:

  1. Wait a minute, theres something off about that team data. How many rows does it have? How many should it?

  2. Can you figure out whats going on and come up with a way to filter out the teams you dont want?

Now we have to link this data into the data frame of players we created above. The way we do this is with a join - specifically, a left_join(). I dont want to get into extreme details, but heres a great diagram that explains whats happening.

Basically, we have two data frames with different information: players18 has data on player performance, and team_data18 has data on team minutes and shots. But if we look closely, they share a variable: TEAM_NAME and team_display_name are the same - the name of the team. We can use that to link these two data frames like so:

# Join team data to player data
players18_team <- players18 %>% 
  left_join(team_data18, by = c("TEAM_NAME" = "team_display_name"))

Defender of the Faith

What about defense? The NBA play-by-play data actually contains data on who the closest defender is on each shot. One thing we could look at, then, is the shooting percentage on all shots where each player is the closest defender.

HW Q1: First, read in the shot chart data, save it as shots18, and then modify the code below to add two variables: the percent of shots taken from 3-pt range, and then the mean distance on 2-pt shots. (1 pt)

players18 <- shots18 %>% 
  
  # Change shot location units to feet (rather than tenths of a foot), 
  # and re-create new precise shot distance variable
  mutate(LOC_X = LOC_X/10,
         LOC_Y = LOC_Y/10,
         SHOT_DISTANCE = sqrt(LOC_X^2 + LOC_Y^2)) %>%

  mutate(pts = case_when(SHOT_TYPE == "3PT Field Goal" ~ 3, # New variable for 2 vs. 3 pt shot
                         TRUE ~ 2)) %>% 
  group_by(PLAYER_NAME, TEAM_NAME) %>% 
  
  #Create a bunch of new variables
  summarize(FGA = n(), # Count rows to get FGA
            FGM = sum(SHOT_MADE_FLAG), # Sum um 0/1 SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get FGM
            
            # Do a "Count If" equivalent to get number of 2 pt and 3pt FGA
            FGA_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2])/2,
            FGA_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3])/3,
            
            # Multiply those "count ifs" by SHOT_MADE_FLAG to get number of each type of FGM
            FGM_2pt = sum(pts[pts==2]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==2])/2,
            FGM_3pt = sum(pts[pts==3]*SHOT_MADE_FLAG[pts==3])/3,
            
            #Add your two new variables here
            ) %>%
  
  ungroup()
